, and theoretical issues. TIMES LITERARY SUPPLEMENTGuest Editors: Sarah Bowden, Susanne Friede and Andreas Hammer This special issue focuses on space and place in Arthurian literature, from a wide range of European traditions. Topics addressed include the connections between quest space and individual spirituality in the Vulgate Queste and Malory's Morte Darthur; penitence in Hartmann's Iwein and Gregorius; parallels in sacred spaces in the Matter of Britain and medieval Ireland; political prophecy in Sir Gawain and the Green Knight and The Awntyrs off Arthure A; syntagmatic and paradigmatic spaces in Chrétien's Perceval; spatial significance in Wigalois and Prosa Lancelot; the political meaning of the tomb of King Lot and the rebel kings in Malory's Morte Darthur; and sexual spaces in twelfth-century French romance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aArthurian Literature.  aMedieval Literature.1 aBaldon, Martha Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowden, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowden, Sarah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarey, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFlood, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriede, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriede, Susanne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHammer, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammer, Andreas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLeitch, Megan G, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRushton, Cory James, econtributor.4ctb4http